title: User query: Plan description from client LLM
log: Make a Wayang Plan that take the cities in interesting_municipalities_cities textfile and returns all organisations which have a matching municipality in the textfile. The textfile only have cities, but a municipality is usually called something like the city. Output the result in a textfile.

title: Agent: SpecifierAgent Output
log:
Build a Wayang plan with the following specification:

- Inputs:
  - A text file named "interesting_municipalities_cities" containing city names (assume one city name per line).
  - An organisations dataset that includes a "municipality" attribute for each organisation.

- Task:
  - Read the list of city names from the text file.
  - Read the organisations dataset.
  - Select all organisations whose "municipality" matches any city name from the text file. Treat matches as case-insensitive and ignore leading/trailing whitespace. Consider a match valid if the city name equals the municipality name or if the city name appears as a substring within the municipality name.

- Output:
  - Write all matching organisation records to a text file.

log.thoughts: Selecting organisation to access municipality and name; selecting interesting_municipalities_cities as the input list of cities to match against municipalities.

steps.detailed_description: Load the text file 'interesting_municipalities_cities' (one city name per line) and the 'organisation' JDBC table with all columns, especially the 'municipality' column.

Normalize both datasets. For the city list: trim leading/trailing whitespace, convert to lowercase, remove empty lines, and deduplicate. For organisations: add a derived field norm_municipality = lowercase(trim(municipality)). Input: raw city lines and full organisation rows. Output: (a) normalized distinct city names; (b) organisation rows augmented with norm_municipality.

Match organisations to the city list using case-insensitive, trimmed logic with substring allowance. Implement as a semi-join/filter: keep an organisation if there exists a city in the normalized city list such that city == norm_municipality OR norm_municipality contains city (substring). Prefer broadcasting the city list to filter organisations for efficiency. Output: filtered organisation rows (original columns; temporary normalization fields may be dropped).
Write all matching organisation records to a text file output.

log.thoughts: Two inputs are normalized first, then a semi-join/contains-based match filters organisations, followed by writing the result. Four concise steps cover input, normalization, matching, and output.

operations.udf: (r: org.apache.wayang.basic.data.Record) => { val organisation_id = r.getField(0).asInstanceOf[Int]; val organisation_no = r.getField(1).asInstanceOf[Int]; val active_organisation = r.getField(2).asInstanceOf[Int]; val name = r.getField(3).toString; val social_housing_org = r.getField(4).toString; val municipality = r.getField(5).toString; val norm_municipality = municipality.trim.toLowerCase; (organisation_id, organisation_no, active_organisation, name, social_housing_org, municipality, norm_municipality) }

log.thoughts: Loaded text file and organisation table (step 1), then normalized cities (trim/lowercase, dedup) and augmented organisations with norm_municipality (step 2). Maintained separate branches for future joins.

operations.udf: (t: ((Int, Int, Int, String, String, String, String), Set[String])) => { val o = t._1; val cities = t._2; val norm = o._7; cities.contains(norm) || cities.exists(c => norm.contains(c)) }
(t: ((Int, Int, Int, String, String, String, String), Set[String])) => { val o = t._1; (o._1, o._2, o._3, o._4, o._5, o._6) }

log.thoughts: Loaded text and JDBC sources (step 1), normalized city lines and augmented organisations with norm_municipality (step 2), then built a semi-join by broadcasting the reduced Set of cities via a constant-key join and filtering organisations by equality or substring match (step 3).

operations.udf: (r: org.apache.wayang.basic.data.Record) => { val muniRaw = r.getField(5); val norm = if (muniRaw == null) "" else muniRaw.toString.trim.toLowerCase; (1, (r, norm)) }
(t: ((Int, Set[String]), (Int, (org.apache.wayang.basic.data.Record, String)))) => { val cities = t._1._2; val rec = t._2._2._1; val norm = t._2._2._2; (rec, norm, cities) }
(t: (org.apache.wayang.basic.data.Record, String, Set[String])) => { val norm = if (t._2 == null) "" else t._2; val cities = t._3; cities.exists(c => c.nonEmpty && (norm == c || norm.contains(c))) }

log.thoughts: Loaded both inputs, normalized cities and municipality, collected cities into a Set via reduce and broadcasted via constant-key join, filtered organisations by equality or substring, formatted for text output, and added output operator with consistent IDs.
